x4freetext: Nitrogen gas sample, 15N
concentration averaged 95 atom percent. Major
contaminants were 16O and 14N. The target thicknesses
were varied in the range from 2 to 4 keV depending on
the cross section.
2-3 mils thick CsI(Tl) crystal mounted on a
Dumont 6291 photomultiplier tube.
Beam energy calibrated using 7Li(p,n)7Be threshold
energy.
Excitation curves were run at six
angles in energy steps from 2 to 5 keV and covered
the energy range from 1.75 to 5.50 MeV. The selection
of the scattering angles was governed by the
dependence of the coherent scattering amplitude on
the orbital angular momentum l. This procedure was
followed since it is possible to obtain an indication
of the l value responsible for a particular resonance
by the disappearance of an anomaly in the excitation
curve at the scattering angle corresponding to a zero
of the Legendre polynomial.
Approximate uncertainty in energy scale.

x4freetext: The computer code MULTI, which employs the
multi-level, multi-channel formalism of R-matrix
theory was used by the University of Florida group in
the calculation of the excitation functions measured
previously by the Columbia University group. The spin
and parity, the reduced width, and resonance energy
for each of the resonances were taken as adjustable
parameters.
